- 2 Acer monitors: AL1722 via DVI, AL1723 via vga.


- lscpi says this about my card:

01:00.0 VGA compatible controller: ATI Technologies Inc RV280 [Radeon 9200]=
 (rev=20
01)
01:00.1 Display controller: ATI Technologies Inc Device 5942 (rev 01)=20


- lsmod (selection):

i2c_dev          14600  0
i2c_algo_bit   14084  1 radeonfb2c_viapro       15892  0
radeonfb         106048  1fb_ddc            10240  1 radeonfb
radeon            342816 2
drm                 96296  3 radeon


- ls -l /dev/i2c*:

crw-rw---- 1 root root 89, 0 2011-05-25 19:09 /dev/i2c-0
crw-rw---- 1 root root 89, 1 2011-05-25 19:09 /dev/i2c-1
crw-rw---- 1 root root 89, 2 2011-05-25 19:09 /dev/i2c-2
crw-rw---- 1 root root 89, 3 2011-05-25 19:09 /dev/i2c-3
crw-rw---- 1 root root 89, 4 2011-05-25 19:09 /dev/i2c-4

Question: why so many i2c devices?


- ddccontrol was executed when I had made /dev/i2c-* files available using=
=20
method described in user guide. Apparently it used both access methods (i2c=
 and=20
direct pci). I used Ubuntu, and thus had to use sudo. I also added the -v=20
option.


- Apparently, ddccontrol only read control data from one of the monitors, t=
he=20
one on analog, ignoring the one on dvi. To get data from that one, I have t=
ried=20
things like "sudo ddccontrol -dc dev:/dev/i2c-{2,3}". The results are attac=
hed.=20
Remarks: because I was dumping to txt en shell with &>, stderr messages app=
ear=20
at the beginning, and then all of stdout (I don't know why). I have marked =
the=20
beginning of stdout with "-----HERE!!". Besides: information obtained from=
=20
monitor on dvi is very terse when compared to that of the one on analog. Wh=
y?


- Executing "sudo gddccontrol" shows similar behaviour to all above, just o=
n a=20
GUI.


Please people, help me.
Greetings,
Marc Albero=

